tics/greg-gianforte-montana-election-article-1.3195401|title=What you need to know about Greg Gianforte and Montana\u2019s election |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n| website = {{url|gianforte.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Gregory Richard Gianforte''' (born April 17, 1961) is an American businessman, tech entrepreneur, engineer, politician, and author serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Montana's at-large congressional district]]. On May 25, 2017, he won the [[Montana's at-large congressional district special election, 2017|special election]]. Gianforte and his wife founded [[RightNow Technologies]], a [[customer relationship management]] software company.<ref name=\"Sky20112\">{{cite web|url=http://msp.imirus.com/Mpowered/book/vds11/i1/p116|title=Native & Newcomer|date=2011|publisher=Delta Airlines|page=114|issn=0734-8967|dead-url=|work=Sky}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Montana gubernatorial election, 2016|2016]], he ran for [[Governor of Montana]] as the Republican candidate, losing to Democratic incumbent Governor [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]]. On May 25, 2017, he won a [[Montana's at-large congressional district special election, 2017|special election]] for [[Montana's at-large congressional district|Montana's at-large congressional seat]].\n\nOn June 12, 2017, Gianforte pleaded guilty in court on a charge of [[Assault|misdemeanor assault]] stemming from his May 24 attack on ''[[The Guardian]]'' political reporter [[Ben Jacobs (journalist)|Ben Jacobs]].<ref name=twsBozeman1>Bozeman Daily Chronicle, Whitney Bermes, October 11, 2017, [https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/judge-releases-congressman-gianforte-s-mugshot/article_af6ccc66-e32d-5b76-9c46-fec7f41e9069.html Judge releases Congressman Gianforte\u2019s mugshot], Retrieved October 11, 2017.</ref> He was sentenced to 40 hours of community service, 20 hours of anger management, a 180-day deferred sentence, and a $300 fine along with an $85 court fee.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/12/politics/greg-gianforte-assault-plea/index.html|title=Gianforte pleads guilty to assault in incident with reporter|last=CNN|first=Kyung Lah, Noa Yadidi and Carma Hassan|website=CNN|access-date=2017-06-12}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/incoming-gop-congressman-greg-gianforte-to-plead-guilty-to-assault-on-reporter-1497280559|title=Incoming GOP Congressman Greg Gianforte Pleads Guilty to Assault on Reporter|last=Andrews|first=Natalie|date=2017-06-12|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2017-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> As part of his settlement with Jacobs, Gianforte donated $50,000 to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], which said it would use the funds to support the U.S. Press Freedom Tracker.<ref name=\"cpj.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/blog/2017/06/cpj-to-use-50000-gianforte-donated-as-part-of-body.php|title=CPJ to use $50,000 Gianforte donated as part of body slam settlement to track other assaults on press  - Committee to Protect Journalists|website=cpj.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>\n\nGianforte officially assumed office on June 21, 2017. {{asof|2018}} he is among the [[List of current members of the United States Congress by wealth|wealthiest members of Congress]].<ref name=\"rollcall\">{{cite web|url=http://media.cq.com/50Richest/|title=Wealth of Congress|publisher=[[Roll Call]]|accessdate = 23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGregory Richard Gianforte<ref name=\"full name\">{{cite web|url=http://www.montana.edu/opa/coms/honorary.html|title=Honorary Degree Committee|publisher=Montana State University|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gregory R. Gianforte Executive Profile & Biography - Bloomberg|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=77562&privcapId=270427|accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref> was born to Frank (1937-2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meaningfulfunerals.net/obituary/frank-gianforte?fh_id=14125|title=Obituary for Frank Richard Gianforte at Mauger Givnish Funeral Home|website=www.meaningfulfunerals.net|language=en|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> and Dale Gianforte (died 2008) in [[San Diego, California]] on April 17, 1961.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/sandiegouniontribune/obituary.aspx?n=dale-douglass-gianforte&pid=105515334|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> He is of [[English people|English]], [[Italians|Italian]], and [[Scottish people|Scottish]] descent.<ref name=\"born\">(March 31, 2007). [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/local/2017/03/31/gianforte-wants-help-montanans-prosper/99860016/ Gianforte wants to help all Montanans prosper], ''USA Today''</ref><ref name=\"dadobit\">(May 6, 2015). [http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/dailylocal/obituary.aspx?pid=174790629 Frank Richard Gianforte], ''The Daily Local''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Dale-Gianforte/6000000049464968056|title=Dale Gianforte|website=geni_family_tree|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref> When he was at a young age, the family moved to the suburbs of [[Philadelphia]], and he graduated from [[Upper Merion Area High School]] in [[King of Prussia, Pennsylvania]] in 1979.<ref name=\"kofp\">(October 26, 2011). [http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq-phillydeals/KofP-prodigy-in-15B-Oracle-cloud-software-deal.html KofP prodigy in $1.5B Oracle cloud software deal], ''Philadelphia Inquirer''</ref> He obtained a [[B.E.]] in electrical engineering and an [[MSc]] in computer science from [[Stevens Institute of Technology]] in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]] in 1983.<ref>Charles Hack, [http://www.nj.com/jjournal-news/index.ssf/2012/09/stevens_institute_in_hoboken_a.html Stevens Institute in Hoboken accepts $10 million gift, largest ever, from Gianforte Family Foundation], ''[[The Jersey Journal]]'' (September 18, 2012).</ref>\n\n==Career in software==\n[[File:GregGianforte (cropped).jpg|thumb|Gianforte speaking in 2006]]\nGianforte co-founded Brightwork Development Inc., a software company, in 1986; he and his partners sold the company to [[McAfee Associates]] for $10&nbsp;million in 1994.<ref>Emily Barker, [https://www.inc.com/magazine/20020201/23855.html Start with Nothing], ''Inc.'' (February 1, 2002).</ref> He then moved to [[Bozeman, Montana]].<ref name=\"kofp\"/>\n \nGianforte founded [[RightNow Technologies]] in 1997. The company [[Initial public offering|went public]] in 2004 and was sold to Oracle Corporation for $1.5&nbsp;billion in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-24/oracle-agrees-to-purchase-rightnow-technologies-for-about-1-5-billion.html |work=Bloomberg |first=Sarah |last=Frier |title=Oracle Buys RightNow for .5 Billion to Add Cloud Services |date=October 24, 2011}}</ref> Before the sale, RightNow Technologies employed about 500 people at its headquarters in Bozeman, Montana, and over 1000 people in total.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flandro |first1=Carly |title=RightNow grows to more than 1,000 employees |url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/article_fba085d8-2f35-11e0-baee-001cc4c002e0.html#user-comment-area |accessdate=July 8, 2015 |work=Bozeman Daily Chronicle |date=February 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nGianforte is a board member of [[FICO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.equilar.com/bio/greg-gianforte-rightnow-technologies/salary/79062|title=Greg R. Gianforte - Executive Bio, Compensation History, and Contacts - Equilar Atlas|work=equilar.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==2016 Montana gubernatorial election==\n{{main|Montana gubernatorial election, 2016}}\n[[File:Republican-GOP Headquarters, Havre, Montana (28816654014) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Gianforte/Robinson campaign sign outside the [[Hill County, Montana|Hill County]] Republican Party headquarters in [[Havre, Montana|Havre]]]]\nOn January 20, 2016, Gianforte announced his candidacy for the Republican Party's nomination for [[governor of Montana]] in the 2016 election.<ref name=\"Lutey2016\">{{cite web |url=http://billingsgazette.com/article_6f4b00b1-a6c8-57dd-9e91-25d5c6235150.html |title=Gianforte declares candidacy for governor in Billings |work=Billings Gazette |date=January 20, 2016 |archive-url=http://webcitation.org/query?date=2016-01-20&url=http%3A%2F%2Fbillingsgazette.com%2Farticle_6f4b00b1-a6c8-57dd-9e91-25d5c6235150.html |archive-date=January 20, 2016 |dead-url=no |first=Tom |last=Lutey |issn=2372-868X}}</ref> He had a political practices complaint filed alleging he started campaigning before registering.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Political practices complaint filed against Gianforte |url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/political-practices-complaint-filed-against-gianforte/article_1650b52f-2c1c-55eb-bc6a-e1fa101addf4.html |accessdate=August 29, 2015 |first=Troy |last=Carter}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Complaint alleges that Gianforte campaigned before registering as a candidate |url=http://www.kxlh.com/story/29911418/complaint-alleges-that-gianforte-campaigned-before-registering-as-a-candidate |accessdate=August 29, 2015 |first=Sanjay |last=Talwani |work=MTN News}}</ref> The complaint was dismissed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carter|first1=Troy|title=Campaign Complaint Against Gianforte Dismissed|url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/campaign-complaint-against-gianforte-dismissed/article_fc53793c-47f0-5230-a45e-f93365bad3a6.html|newspaper=Bozeman Daily Chronicle|accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a campaign speech that year, Gianforte stated that he had been involved in discussions with [[Facebook]] about bringing a new call center to Montana, but that Facebook had declined because of that state's business equipment tax.<ref>Phil Drake, [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/local/2016/04/18/gianforte-unveils-tax-relief-plan/83202158/ Gianforte unveils '406 Tax Relief' plan], ''Great Falls Tribune'' (April 18, 2016).</ref> A Facebook spokesman disputed Gianforte's claims, saying that no discussions with Gianforte took place and that the tax was not the reason the company decided not to locate a call center in Montana. Gianforte stood by his statement saying that he had spoken with a Facebook executive the previous fall.<ref>Associated Press, [http://kopr94.net/facebook-disputes-montana-candidates-claim/ Facebook disputes claims of Montana candidate] (April 21, 2016).</ref>\n\n[[Steve Bullock (Montana politician)|Steve Bullock]], the incumbent Democratic governor, defeated Gianforte in the November general election, 50%\u201346%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sos.mt.gov/Portals/142/Elections/archives/2010s/2016/2016GeneralStatewideCanvass.pdf|title=2016 Statewide General Election Canvass|publisher=Montana Secretary of State}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2017====\n{{main|Montana's at-large congressional district special election, 2017}}\nOn March 1, 2017, [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] U.S. Representative [[Ryan Zinke]] of [[Montana's at-large congressional district]] resigned his seat following his confirmation by the [[United States Senate]] as [[United States Secretary of the Interior]]. Governor Bullock set a special election to finish Zinke's term for May 25 that same day.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lutey|first=Tom|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/zinke-confirmed-as-interior-secretary-montana-prepares-for-special-election/article_0a0b705b-2f91-5bc5-8ffb-aa7e666c47aa.html|title=Zinke sworn in as Interior secretary; Montana prepares for special election|work=[[Billings Gazette]]|date=March 1, 2017|accessdate=March 11, 2017}}</ref> Gianforte had already announced his intention to seek the seat on January 25, prior to Zinke's confirmation and subsequent resignation.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dennison|first=Mike|url=http://www.ktvh.com/2017/01/gianforte-officially-enters-the-race-to-succeed-zinke|title=Gianforte officially enters the race to succeed Zinke|publisher=[[KTVH-DT]]|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=March 11, 2017}}</ref> At a March 6 convention, the Republican Party selected Gianforte as their nominee. He faced [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] musician and former Montana Arts Council member [[Rob Quist]], as well as [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] nominee Mark Wicks, in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|author=Holly K. Michels|url=http://missoulian.com/news/government-and-politics/greg-gianforte-wins-republican-nomination-for-montana-s-us-house/article_e4977536-5df1-59be-8b90-5d6c5b845e95.html|title=Greg Gianforte wins Republican nomination for Montana's US House election|newspaper=Missoulian|date=March 6, 2017|accessdate=March 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis campaign was supported by Vice President [[Mike Pence]] and [[Donald Trump Jr.]], who both stumped for Gianforte in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/local/vice-president-mike-pence-in-billings-we-need-greg-gianforte/article_ef2b827a-96c3-5bee-ac72-98658024657d.html|title=Vice President Mike Pence in Billings: 'We need Greg Gianforte' in Congress|author=Hudson, Matt|newspaper=[[Billings Gazette]]|date=May 12, 2017|accessdate=May 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/bernie-sanders-heads-montana-high-profile-house-race-n762386|title=Bernie Sanders heads to Montana for high-profile House race|work=NBC News|access-date=May 20, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/montana/articles/2017-04-12/donald-trump-jr-to-campaign-for-gianforte|title=donald-trump-jr-to-campaign-for-gianforte|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> According to the [[The New York Times|''New York Times'']], Gianforte has in the 2017 race for [[Montana's at-large congressional district]] \"hewed particularly close to the president's narrative: He promotes his outsider status (he has never held office) and his business acumen (his software empire, RightNow Technologies, started in a basement), and takes aim at sanctuary states and \"the liberal elite\" whenever he can.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/22/us/montana-special-election-trump.html|title=What Scandal? In Montana Race, a Republican Is Following the Trump Playbook|last=Turkewitz|first=Julie|date=May 22, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 23, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn financial disclosure forms filed in 2017, Gianforte indicated that he owned $150,000 worth of shares in VanEck Vectors Russia ETF and $92,400 in the IShares MSCF Russia ETF, totalling just under $250,000 in two [[exchange-traded fund]]s focused on investments in Russia.<ref name=\"Jacobs\"/> The investments attracted attention because they included shares in [[Gazprom]] and [[Rosneft]], which are subject to U.S. sanctions imposed after the [[International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis|Russian invasion of Crimea]]; however, because the per-person ownership stake in these companies is so small in such [[index fund]]s, they are exempt from sanctions.<ref name=\"Jacobs\"/> After the issue was raised in Gianforte's 2017 congressional campaign, Gianforte stated that his Russia holdings were a small portion of his overall investments and pledged to place all of his assets in a [[blind trust]] if elected.<ref name=\"Jacobs\"/><ref>Bobby Caina Calvan, [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/investment-russia-becomes-focus-congressional-race/ Investments in Russia become focus in congressional race], Associated Press (April 30, 2017).</ref>\n\n====Assault of reporter====\nOn May 24, 2017, the day before the U.S. House special election, [[Ben Jacobs (journalist)|Ben Jacobs]], a political reporter for ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper who was covering the election, said that Gianforte assaulted him.<!--Where did this take place? It doesn't make sense to not include this information if we intend this article to be properly encyclopedic.--><ref name=\"GuardianUS\">{{cite news|last1=Wong|first1=Julia Carrie|last2=Levin|first2=Sam|title=Republican candidate 'body-slams' Guardian reporter in Montana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/24/greg-gianforte-bodyslams-reporter-ben-jacobs-montana|publisher=[[The Guardian]]/[[Guardian News and Media Limited|Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=May 24, 2017|date=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/reporter-alleges-greg-gianforte-body-slammed-him-in-bozeman/article_9df533bb-9919-51aa-8d0d-5d5cb4e48923.html|title=Reporter alleges Greg Gianforte 'body slammed' him in Bozeman|date=May 25, 2017|publisher=Bozeman Daily Chronicle|accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{cite tweet|number=867517225820966912|user=Bencjacobs|title=Greg Gianforte just body slammed me and broke my glasses|date=May 24, 2017|access-date=May 24, 2017|language=en|link=https://twitter.com/Bencjacobs/status/867517225820966912|last=Jacobs|first=Ben}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/greg-gianforte-allegedly-assault-guardian-reporter|title=Greg Gianforte Allegedly Assault Guardian Reporter|date=May 25, 2017|website=Roll Call|access-date=May 25, 2017}}</ref> Jacobs said that Gianforte \"[[Professional wrestling throws#Body slam|bodyslammed\"]] him to the floor and broke the reporter's glasses.<ref name=\"GuardianUS\"/><ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":12\" /> The Gianforte campaign was initially unapologetic, blaming the reporter,<ref name=twsWashPost855>Amber Phillips, May 26, 2017, Washington Post, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/26/the-gops-newest-member-of-congress-cant-make-up-his-mind-about-whether-he-assaulted-a-reporter-or-a-reporter-assaulted-him/?wpisrc=nl_fix&wpmm=1 The GOP\u2019s newest member of Congress can\u2019t make up his mind about whether he assaulted a reporter, or a reporter assaulted him], Retrieved May 27, 2017, \"...That was 24 hours before Election Day. Gianforte stuck with his story and laid low, even though he was pretty much the only one who seemed to believe himself \u2014 especially after audio of the altercation and eyewitnesses appeared to corroborate Jacobs's account....\"</ref> disputing the allegations, saying that Jacobs grabbed Gianforte's wrist, causing them both to fall to the ground.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/05/25/guardians-ben-jacobs-alleges-greg-gianforte-body-slammed-him/344454001/|title=Reporter alleges he was 'body slammed' by Montana GOP candidate|work=USA TODAY|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> However, an audio recording of the incident appeared to support Jacobs's statement,<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/24/us/politics/gop-candidate-in-montana-house-race-is-accused-of-attacking-reporter.html?_r=0|title=G.O.P. Candidate in Montana House Race Is Accused of Attacking Reporter|date=May 25, 2017|publisher=New York Times|last1=Martin|first1=Jonathan|accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianUS\" /> and other reporters who were present at the scene corroborated Jacobs' version of events.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/05/24/greg-gianforte-fox-news-team-witnesses-gop-house-candidate-body-slam-reporter.html|title=Greg Gianforte: Fox News team witnesses GOP House candidate 'body slam' reporter|last=Acuna|first=Alicia|date=May 24, 2017|work=Fox News|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Fox News]] reporter Alicia Acuna, who witnessed the incident, \"Gianforte grabbed Jacobs by the neck with both hands and slammed him into the ground,\" then \"began punching the man\" and \"yelling something to the effect of 'I'm sick and tired of this!{{' \"}}; Acuna added that Jacobs was not showing \"physical aggression\" prior to the altercation.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/05/24/greg-gianforte-fox-news-team-witnesses-gop-house-candidate-body-slam-reporter.html Greg Gianforte: Fox News team witnesses GOP House candidate 'body slam' reporter]. Acuna, Alicia. [[Fox News]], May 24, 2017</ref> Following the incident, Jacobs went to the hospital for [[x-ray]]s.<ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\nGianforte was cited for [[Assault#United States|misdemeanor assault]] by the Gallatin County Sheriff and was ordered to appear in court regarding his actions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gianforte charged with election-eve assault|url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/gianforte-charged-with-election-eve-assault/article_9df533bb-9919-51aa-8d0d-5d5cb4e48923.html|accessdate=May 25, 2017|publisher=Bozeman Daily Chronicle|date=May 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Update on Assault Investigation|url=https://www.gallatinmedia.org/?p=4732|accessdate=May 25, 2017|publisher=Gallatin County Sheriff|date=May 25, 2017}}</ref> Although he was not arrested, he had to go through customary booking procedures.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/aug/21/greg-gianforte-booking-fingerprinting-mugshot-assault-case</ref>\n\nThree of Montana's largest newspapers, including the ''[[Billings Gazette]]'', the largest in the state, the ''[[Missoulian]]'' and the ''[[Independent Record]]'', all rescinded their endorsements of Gianforte in the wake of the incident.<ref name=\"gazette\">{{cite news|title=Gazette opinion: We're pulling our endorsement of Gianforte|url=http://billingsgazette.com/opinion/editorial/gazette-opinion-we-re-pulling-our-endorsement-of-gianforte/article_34d90b42-545b-5e10-9355-605b7c5cb11f.html|accessdate=May 25, 2017|publisher=Billings Gazette|date=May 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Missoulian rescinds Gianforte endorsement|url=http://missoulian.com/opinion/editorial/missoulian-rescinds-gianforte-endorsement/article_ab947a9d-9220-5dc5-9193-f1ae9ef03c60.html|accessdate=May 25, 2017|publisher=Missoulian|date=May 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Independent Record withdraws endorsement of Gianforte|url=http://helenair.com/news/local/independent-record-withdraws-endorsement-of-gianforte/article_0d7d40b6-8d5d-587c-86f7-290a611b53db.html|accessdate=May 25, 2017|publisher=Independent Record|date=May 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/24/us/politics/greg-gianforte-montana-republican-body-slams-reporter.html|title=Greg Gianforte, Montana G.O.P. Candidate, Is Charged in Attack on Reporter|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=May 24, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 25, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Speaker [[Paul Ryan]] and other members of Congress urged Gianforte to apologize.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/05/25/greg-gianforte-body-slam-paul-ryan-238822|title=Ryan: Gianforte should apologize for alleged assault on reporter|publisher=politico.com|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGianforte won the special election on May 25. During his acceptance speech that evening, he apologized to Jacobs and the Fox News crew for his assault.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gianforte: 'I made a mistake, I am sorry'|url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2017/05/26/gianforte-apology-sot-speech.cnn|website=CNN|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref> On June 7 Gianforte made a written apology to Jacobs and donated US$50,000 to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], which accepted the funds because it was part of the settlement and said it would put them towards the U.S. Press Freedom Tracker.<ref name=\"cpj.org\"/> In return, Jacobs agreed to not pursue a civil claim against Gianforte.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wong|first1=Julia Carrie|title=Gianforte pays $50,000 to press group to settle assault of Guardian reporter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jun/07/greg-gianforte-ben-jacobs-assault-case-civil-settlement?CMP=share_btn_tw|accessdate=June 23, 2017|work=The Guardian|date=June 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, 2017, Gianforte pleaded guilty and was originally sentenced to four days in jail, to be completed in part through a work program. However, he was ineligible for the work program due to the assault conviction. The judge then switched the sentence to 40 hours of community service, 20 hours of anger management, 180-day deferred sentence, and a $300 fine along with an $85 court fee.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nDuring the court hearing Jacobs said that he hoped to interview Gianforte in the future, as he was trying to do at the time of the assault. Gianforte said in court to Jacobs \"I am sorry, and if and when you are ready, I look forward to sitting down with you in D.C.\" However, Gianforte later refused Jacobs an on-the-record interview.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/08/29/media/ben-jacobs-greg-gianforte-interview-dispute/index.html |title=Body-slammed reporter wants to know why Rep. Gianforte still won't grant interview  |newspaper=CNN |date=29 August 2017  |author=Brian Stelter |accessdate= 12 October 2017}}</ref> Gianforte also tried to avoid having an official photograph (\"mugshot\") taken until compelled by court order. ''The Guardian'' reported in October that the mugshot had been released publicly by a judge's order, and added \"The Congressman has reneged on a courtroom offer to sit down with Jacobs for an interview.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/oct/11/greg-gianfortes-mugshot-released-to-the-public-after-legal-battle |title=Greg Gianforte's mugshot released to the public after legal battle |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 October 2017  |author=Sabrina Siddiqui|accessdate= 12 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nA report in November 2017 suggested that Gianforte initially had misled police about the attack, saying that Jacobs had initiated contact and had blamed the story on \"liberal media.\"<ref name=twsGuardian435>Julia Carrie Wong, 18 November 2017, The Guardian, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/nov/17/greg-gianforte-guardian-reporter-ben-jacobs-assault?subid=21785878&CMP=GT_US_collection Greg Gianforte misled police after assault of Guardian journalist, incident report shows: Montana congressman falsely said Ben Jacobs had initiated physical contact: Gianforte told police \u2018the liberal media is trying to make a story\u2019], Retrieved November 18, 2017</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/11/17/rep-gianfortes-account-to-police-of-assault-with-reporter-appears-to-contradict-his-later-apology-new-report-shows/|title=Rep. Gianforte\u2019s account to police on assault of reporter appears to contradict his later apology|last=Silverman|first=Ellie|date=2017-11-17|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-11-22|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nGianforte was sworn into the U.S. House on June 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Republican Convicted of Attacking Reporter Joins House | url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/06/21/republican-convicted-attacking-reporter-joins-house.html | date=June 21, 2017 | publisher=[[Fox News]] (from the [[Associated Press]]) | accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref> At his inauguration ceremony, Gianforte announced his support for congressional term limits, barring members of Congress from becoming lobbyists, and holding back congressional pay if no budget is passed \u2013 it is unusual for members of Congress to announce such support for legislation in their inauguration.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Marcos | first1=Cristina | title=Gianforte Causes Stir After Becoming Newest House Member | url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/338813-gianforte-causes-stir-after-becoming-newest-house-member | date=June 21, 2017 | publisher=''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' | accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref> Montana Democrats mailed Gianforte an orange prison jumpsuit at the day of his inauguration.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Shelbourne | first1=Mallory | title=Montana Dems Send Orange Jumpsuit for Gianforte's First Day in Congress | url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/338838-montana-dems-send-gianforte-orange-jumpsuit-for-first-day-in-congress | date=June 21, 2017 | publisher=''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' | accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Chasmar | first1=Jessica | title=Montana Democrats Mail Orange Jumpsuit to Greg Gianforte | url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jun/21/montana-democrats-mail-orange-jumpsuit-to-greg-gia/ | date=June 21, 2017 | publisher=''[[The Washington Times]]'' | accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\n\n=== Abortion ===\nGianforte opposes [[abortion]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ktvq.com/story/33501881/mt-govs-race-features-big-difference-on-social-issues-but-gianforte-says-not-that-relevant|title=MT gov's race features big difference on social issues \u2013 but Gianforte says it's not that relevant|author=Mike Dennison|publisher=MNT News (KTVH)|date=October 27, 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/steve-bullock-vs-greg-gianforte-nonpartisan-candidate_us_580ecdf8e4b0f871578a0008|title=Steve Bullock vs. Greg Gianforte: Nonpartisan Candidate Guide For 2016 Montana Governor\u2019s Race|last=Project|first=Campus Election Engagement|date=October 25, 2016|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> He believes that abortion should be prohibited except when the woman's life is in danger.<ref name=\"Michels\">Holly K. Michels, [http://missoulian.com/news/local/gianforte-supports-defunding-planned-parenthood-quist-approves-of-legalizing-recreational/article_706f57a2-d8bd-5d15-bd5d-96cd1596bfc1.html Gianforte supports defunding Planned Parenthood; Quist approves of legalizing recreational marijuana], ''Missoulian'' (April 29, 2017).</ref> Gianforte favors removing federal funds from [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref name=\"Michels\"/>\n\nThe Gianforte Family Foundation was founded to pursue Gianforte's creationist beliefs in the public sphere and to \"protect the unborn.\" The foundation has been a part of anti-abortion campaigns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Governor/Greg_Gianforte_Abortion.htm|title=Greg Gianforte on Abortion|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=2017-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Aging and retirement===\n\nGianforte has outlined his position on retirement by using the Biblical example of [[Noah]]. He said:<blockquote>\"There's nothing in the Bible that talks about retirement. And yet it's been an accepted concept in our culture today. Nowhere does it say, 'Well, he was a good and faithful servant, so he went to the beach... The example I think of is Noah. How old was Noah when he built the ark? 600. He wasn't like, cashing Social Security checks, he wasn't hanging out, he was working. So, I think we have an obligation to work. The role we have in work may change over time, but the concept of retirement is not biblical.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Governor/Greg_Gianforte_Social_Security.htm|title=Greg Gianforte on Social Security|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=April 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/gianforte-potential-gop-governor-candidate-protested-by-billings-democrats/article_8ccde528-6d3a-5e4d-a9c3-aabdb0c1757d.html|title=Gianforte, potential GOP governor candidate, protested by Billings Democrats|last=Lutey|first=Tom|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=April 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/693863/montana-republican-running-special-election-doesnt-believe-retirement-because-noah-still-working-when-600|title=The Montana Republican running in the special election doesn't believe in retirement because Noah was still working when he was 600|date=April 21, 2017|access-date=April 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/06/09/greg-gianforte-montana_n_7536568.html|title=Noah From The Bible Didn't Retire, So This Likely GOP Gubernatorial Candidate Doesn't See Why You Should|last=Lachman|first=Samantha|date=June 9, 2015|work=Huffington Post|access-date=April 29, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Creationism ===\nGianforte believes in [[Young Earth creationism]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ncse.com/cej/6/2/scientific-creationism-as-pseudoscience|title=\"Scientific\" Creationism as a Pseudoscience - NCSE|website=ncse.com|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref> and has expressed support for the pseudoscientific view despite overwhelming scientific evidence to the contrary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/25/us/greg-gianforte-facts.html|title=Who Is Greg Gianforte?|first=Alexander|last=Burns|date=May 25, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=May 30, 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> He has donated at least $290K in cash to the [[Glendive Dinosaur and Fossil Museum]], a Montana [[creationist museum]] which teaches visitors that [[evolution]] is false, the Earth is about 6,000-6,400 years old, that dinosaurs were on [[Noah's Ark|the Ark]] and that they likely died out 4,300 years ago during the flood described in the [[Book of Genesis]], and which is regarded as wholly deceptive and fictional, with noted palaeontologist Jack Horner calling it \"not a museum at all\".<ref>http://billingsgazette.com/news/features/magazine/dinosaur-museum-presents-biblical-view-of-origins/article_1c9ac218-bab0-11de-84f1-001cc4c002e0.html</ref><!--NOTE: sources do not verify prior claims that Gianforte contributed more than $1,000,000 to the museum -- $290K in cash and the dinosaur exhibits, for which no value has been assigned.--><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/04/billionaire-tech-ceo-laying-groundwork-for-montana-gubernatorial-run/434625/|title=Billionaire Tech CEO Laying Groundwork for Montana Gubernatorial Run|last=Bruggeman|first=Karyn|work=The Atlantic|date=April 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Kristen Inbody|url=http://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/life/my-montana/2016/04/28/dinosaurs-bible-glendive-museum/83681042/|title=Dinosaurs, the Bible and a Glendive museum|work=Great Falls Tribune|date=April 28, 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Healy2009\">{{cite web|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/features/magazine/dinosaur-museum-presents-biblical-view-of-origins/article_1c9ac218-bab0-11de-84f1-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Dinosaur museum presents biblical view of origins: A faith-based Creation|last=Healy|first=Donna|date=October 18, 2009|issn=2372-868X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629215555/http://billingsgazette.com/news/features/magazine/dinosaur-museum-presents-biblical-view-of-origins/article_1c9ac218-bab0-11de-84f1-001cc4c002e0.html|archive-date=June 29, 2013|dead-url=no|newspaper=Billings Gazette|df=}}</ref> The Gianforte Family Foundation also donated a [[Tyrannosaurus rex]] skeleton replica to the [[Glendive Dinosaur and Fossil Museum]] in [[Glendive, Montana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/features/magazine/dinosaur-museum-presents-biblical-view-of-origins/article_1c9ac218-bab0-11de-84f1-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Dinosaur museum presents biblical view of origins|first=DONNA HEALY Of The Gazette|last=Staff|publisher=|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\nGianforte distanced himself from Donald Trump during the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Republican primary]] and did not attend his one rally in Montana, citing a scheduling conflict.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-montana-special-election-trump-20170520-story.html|title=Montana Republican goes from wary Trump backer to all-in ahead of election|last=Riccardi|first=Matt Volz and Nicholas|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2017-05-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/republicans-who-didn-t-support-trump-in-early-now-are/article_8e58cc92-b79b-5dde-9a24-956b5fdfdae0.html|title=Republicans who didn't support Trump in early 2016 now are all in|last=Lutey|first=Tom|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=April 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref> However, he endorsed Trump in the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 general election]] and continued to express support for him during his House campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ravallirepublic.com/news/local/article_5f5f766e-2aa9-11e6-989a-db424d8af079.html|title=GOP candidates discuss issues, support Trump|last=McConnaha|first=Michelle|work=Ravalli Republic|access-date=April 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Volz | first1=Matt | last2=Riccardi | first2=Nicholas | title=Greg Gianforte Goes from Wary Trump Backer to All-In | url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/greg-gianforte-goes-from-wary-trump-backer-to-all-in/article_753ec22b-2f8e-5b08-b64e-b589e8213888.html | date=May 20, 2017 | publisher=''[[Billings Gazette]]'' | accessdate=May 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcmontana.com/news/montana/montana-republican-goes-from-wary-trump-backer-to-all-in/5085470175|title=Montana Republican goes from wary Trump backer to all-in|last=News|first=N. B. C.|date=May 20, 2017|website=NBC News|access-date=May 25, 2017}}</ref> Gianforte has supported Trump's [[2017 United States federal hiring freeze|2017 hiring freeze]],<ref name=\"Kuglin\">Tim Kuglin, [http://helenair.com/news/politics/state/gianforte-i-believe-we-can-develop-natural-resources-and-protect/article_658138f7-a25c-5066-9dd2-338bd34baae6.html Gianforte: 'I believe we can develop natural resources and protect the environment'], ''Helena Independent Record'' (April 28, 2017).</ref> his decision to [[Dismissal of James Comey|fire FBI Director James Comey]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/10/politics/republicans-stick-with-trump-on-comey-firing/index.html|title=Republicans on ballots stick with Trump on Comey firing|last=CNN|first=Eric Bradner|website=CNN|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> and [[Executive Order 13769]], which temporarily banned immigration from seven Middle Eastern and predominantly Muslim countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/montanas-special-election/story?id=47533835|title=What to know about Montana's special election|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=May 23, 2017|website=ABC News|access-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment and public lands ===\nGianforte opposes the sale or transfer of federal land. He has called for changes to the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=\"Kuglin\" /> Gianforte has also called for changes to the federal [[Equal Access to Justice Act]] to reduce environmental litigation, asserting that the act has been abused by \"environmental extremists.\"<ref name=\"Kuglin\" />\n\nIn an April 2017 interview, Gianforte acknowledged [[Attribution of recent climate change|human-caused]] [[Global warming|climate change]] but \"did not have specific ideas on how to address climate change.\"<ref name=\"Kuglin\" /> In another April 2017 interview, however, he said that \"the climate is always changing,\" and stated that closing coal-fired power plants would not help [[Climate change mitigation|mitigate climate change]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/quist-gianforte-support-coal-but-differ-on-policy/article_b6cbf2b9-7b14-5f6a-96ae-4817fd9511ec.html|title=Quist, Gianforte support coal, but differ on policy|last=Lutey|first=Tom|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=May 14, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He supported Trump's repeal of the [[Clean Power Plan]] introduced by the Obama administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/trump-s-repeal-of-clean-power-plan-gets-mixed-montana/article_c71f60b9-46a2-5d0b-822b-34833101959f.html|title=Trump's repeal of Clean Power Plan gets mixed Montana reception|last=Lutey|first=Tom|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=May 14, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nManagement of public lands was a point of contention in both Gianforte's 2016 campaign for governor<ref name=\"Fraser\">Jayme Fraser, [http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-gianforte-spar-over-access-to-public-lands/article_cda4f862-a9e2-559f-b2d7-91bc497d8d4c.html Bullock, Gianforte spar over access to public lands], Missourian (July 22, 2016).</ref> and Gianforte's campaign for Congress.<ref name=\"Frost\">Mikenzie Frost,\n [http://www.ktvh.com/2017/04/records-show-quist-gianforte-have-different-hunting-and-fishing-history Records show Quist, Gianforte have different hunting and fishing history], KTVH (April 26, 2017).</ref> In 2009, Gianforte's [[Limited liability company|LLC]] filed a lawsuit against the [[Montana Department of Fish, Wildlife and Parks]] about the boundaries of an easement for public access to the East Gallatin River.<ref name=\"FraserMichels\">Hayme Fraser & Holly Michels, [http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/governor-candidate-gianforte-sued-state-in-over-access-to-river/article_951b0234-304c-5570-b90e-83e92fb8c976.html Governor candidate Gianforte sued state in 2009 over access to river], ''Billings Gazette'' (May 10, 2016).</ref> Gianforte's suit against the state became an issue in the 2016 campaign with Gianforte's critics characterizing it as a wealthy out-of-stater's effort to block public access to a popular stream.<ref name=\"Fraser\" /><ref name=\"FraserMichels\" /><ref name=\"Kuglin\" /> Gianforte \"has consistently denied the allegations and called the issue a misunderstanding, noting the suit was never served.\" In any case, the matter was settled.<ref name=\"Fraser\" /> In his 2017 campaign for Congress, Gianforte's campaign spokesperson stated that Gianforte believes that \"public lands need to stay in public hands and he opposes efforts to transfer federal lands to the states.\"<ref name=\"Frost\" />\n\nHe has called for investments in clean coal technology.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nGianforte supports repeal of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missoulian.com/news/government-and-politics/gianforte-quist-both-say-current-bill-to-replace-obamacare-needs/article_5c4b5bf1-8ef4-5e97-8a63-8a196d302b66.html|title=Gianforte, Quist both say current bill to replace Obamacare needs work|author=Holly K. Michels|work=Missoulian|access-date=April 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He has declined to say whether he supports the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]], the House Republican legislation to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/05/us/politics/montana-house-special-election-greg-gianforte-health-bill.html|title=G.O.P. House Candidate in Montana Is Caught on Tape Praising Health Bill|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=May 5, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 10, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> That same day, Gianforte held a private conference call with Republican-leaning lobbyists in Washington D.C. where he offered a more supportive view of the American Health Care Act.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/05/19/montana-democrat-closes-with-health-care-message-in-closely-watched-congressional-race/|title=Montana Democrat closes with health-care message in closely watched congressional race|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 20, 2017}}</ref> He said that it \"sounds like we just passed a health care thing, which I'm thankful for, sounds like we're starting to repeal and replace.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Later that May, he said he would not \"vote for a repeal and a replace unless I know it protects people with pre-existing conditions, lowers rates and preserves rural access\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcmontana.com/news/ktvm/gianforte-draws-on-business-campaign-experience-ahead-of-special-election/512007308|title=Gianforte draws on business, campaign experience ahead of special election|last=Wadley|first=Will|date=May 23, 2017|work=KECI|access-date=May 23, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe incident where Gianforte assaulted a reporter was in response to questions about how the AHCA would make health insurance too expensive for people with pre-existing conditions.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/05/26/530103144/republican-gianforte-wins-montana-house-race-amid-assault-charge|title=Republican Gianforte Wins Montana House Race Amid Assault Charge|website=NPR.org|access-date=2017-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nGianforte opposes [[sanctuary cities]]<ref name=\":5\"/> and resettlement of refugees in Montana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Greg_Gianforte.htm|title=Greg Gianforte on the Issues|last=OnTheIssues.org|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights===\nGianforte opposes [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]],<ref name=\":1\"/> and has stated that he supports government enforcement of nondiscrimination for workers, but not for customers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/gianforte-clarifies-stance-on-protection-of-lgbt-rights/article_4cef80e6-f5f0-5f2a-88a1-99571513f718.html|title=Gianforte clarifies stance on protection of LGBT rights|last=Lutey|first=Tom|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/dominicholden/republican-for-montana-governor-anti-lgbt-past|title=Republican Frontrunner For Montana Governor Has An Extreme Anti-LGBT Past|author=Dominic Holden|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGianforte has donated to the [[Family Research Council]], and [[Focus on the Family]], which advocates for a constitutional amendment prohibiting same-sex marriage; and the Montana Family Foundation, which is \"the state's primary advocate against LGBT policies\".<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n===Marijuana===\nGianforte opposes the [[Legality of cannabis|legalization of marijuana]] for recreational use, comparing marijuana to more addictive drugs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rob-quist-montana-house-race_us_590628f1e4b05c3976805500|title=Montana Democratic Candidate Affirms Support For Legalizing Marijuana|last=Fang|first=Marina|date=April 30, 2017|work=[[Huffington Post]]|access-date=May 14, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> He supports allowing the use of [[medical marijuana]] to \"people in chronic pain, under the care of a doctor.\"<ref name=\"Michels\" />\n\n=== Minimum wage ===\nGianforte opposes increases in the minimum wage, asserting \"Legislating higher wages actually reduces employment opportunities for people.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/ideas-roll-in-as-gianforte-kicks-off-regulation-roundup-tour/article_e01e24dc-bee7-5cc0-8195-444c024b4621.html|title=Ideas roll in as Gianforte kicks off 'Regulation Roundup Tour'|last=tlutey@billingsgazette.com|first=TOM LUTEY|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=May 14, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Russia ===\nGianforte has blamed the [[Obama administration]] for \"the situation with Russia\" and has stated that: \"The US and our allies need to work together on a long-term strategy to stand against Russian aggression in the region and to ensure the sovereignty of our allies is protected.\"<ref name=\"Jacobs\">Ben Jacobs, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/apr/28/greg-gianforte-republican-candidate-congress-russia-companies GOP candidate has financial ties to US-sanctioned Russian companies], The Guardian'' (April 28, 2017).</ref>\n\n==Gianforte Family Foundation==\nIn 2004, Gianforte and his wife founded the Gianforte Family Foundation, which has made tens of millions of dollars in charitable contributions<ref>Associated Press. \"Gianforte releases tax returns showing income of $220&nbsp;million over 10 years.\" Billings Gazette. March 1, 2016. [http://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/gianforte-releases-tax-returns-showing-income-of-m-over-years/article_788f2715-20c5-536a-98ce-258aa68f40b8.html Billingsgazettecom]. Date Retrieved April 2, 2016</ref><ref name=Viebeck>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/gianforte-has-history-of-controversial-views-hostile-comments-to-press/2017/05/25/ceab14bc-4144-11e7-8c25-44d09ff5a4a8_story.html|title=Gianforte has a history of controversial views and hostile comments to journalists|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 25, 2017|accessdate=May 25, 2017|last=Viebeck|first=Elise}}</ref> and describes as its primary mission to \"support the work of faith-based organizations engaged in outreach work, strengthening families, and helping the needy; organizations in Montana that work to improve education, support entrepreneurship, and create jobs; and organizations that enhance the local community of Bozeman, Montana.\"<ref name=\"Foundation\">{{cite web|url=http://gianfortefoundation.org/about|title=About Us|work=gianfortefoundation.org|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref> He, his wife, and his son are the foundation's three board members.<ref name=\"Foundation\"/> The foundation had assets of $113 million in 2013.<ref name=Viebeck/>\n\nThe Gianforte Family Foundation has given nearly $900,000 to the Montana Family Foundation, in some years making up half of the total donations to the Montana Family Foundation. The Montana Family Foundation has promoted conservative and Christian values in the Montana legislature. Asked why he donated to the group, Gianforte said it was because the organization aligns with his views.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missoulian.com/news/government-and-politics/greg-gianforte-is-significant-backer-of-montana-foundation-that-promotes/article_e2d4958e-1a06-5480-bb4c-a26bb9f70189.html|title=Greg Gianforte is significant backer of Montana foundation that promotes conservative values|last=holly.michels@lee.net|first=HOLLY K. MICHELS|work=missoulian.com|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nGianforte received an honorary doctorate from Stevens Institute of Technology and gave the commencement speech in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2012/5/prweb9506195.htm|title=Greg Gianforte and Jeong Kim Announced as Stevens Institute of Technology's 2012 Commencement Speakers|work=prweb.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Gianforte was awarded an honorary doctorate from Montana State University's College of Engineering.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Carol|title=Four to receive MSU honorary doctorate degrees|url=http://www.montana.edu/news/4734/four-to-receive-msu-honorary-doctorate-degrees|accessdate=July 8, 2015|work=MSU News Service|date=April 3, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"full name\"/>\n\nIn 2007, Gianforte was inducted into the CRM Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destinationcrm.com/Articles/Editorial/Magazine-Features/The-2007-Market-Awards-Hall-of-Fame-41832.aspx|title=The 2007 Market Awards: Hall of Fame|first=the Editors of ''CRM''|last=magazine|date=September 1, 2007|work=destinationcrm.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref> Gianforte received the 2003 Stevens Institute of Technology's Stevens Honor Award.<ref>[http://www.stevens.edu/alumni/News_&_Publications/Alumniletter/ALSep_Oct03/PDFs/AL_Sept-Oct_03.pdf Stevens Institute of Technology's Stevens Honor Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040906203906/http://www.stevens.edu/alumni/News_%26_Publications/Alumniletter/ALSep_Oct03/PDFs/AL_Sept-Oct_03.pdf|date=September 6, 2004}}</ref>\n\nGianforte was named Pacific Northwest [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Awards|Entrepreneur of the Year]] by [[Ernst & Young]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Ernst%20&%20Young%20Names%20RightNow%20Founder%20Greg%20Gianforte%20Pacific%20Northwest...-a0103998791|title=Ernst & Young Names RightNow Founder Greg Gianforte Pacific Northwest Entrepreneur of the Year; Innovation, Outstanding Business Performance, and Personal Commitment Cited in Software Category Award Presentation. - Free Online Library|work=thefreelibrary.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGreg and Susan Gianforte married in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Greg|url=https://gregformontana.com/about|work=GregforMontana.com|accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref> They live in [[Bozeman, Montana]] and have four children.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Greg|url=http://www.gregformontana.com/about-greg|publisher=gregformontana.com|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThey attend Grace Bible Church, a [[Nondenominational Christianity|nondenominational]] church in Bozeman. Gianforte is a donor to several Christian and conservative groups.<ref name=\"Giving\">{{cite web|url=http://helenair.com/news/politics/state/gianforte-s-charitable-giving-reveals-social-conservatism-not-discussed-in/article_8a6e4c34-81df-5161-b823-1e861d8c04d6.html|title=Gianforte's charitable giving reveals social conservatism not discussed in campaign|date=March 27, 2016|publisher=helenair.com|last1=Fraser|first1=Jayme|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Noon|first1=Alison|title=Religion Central to Gianforte's Life, But Not His Campaign|url=http://flatheadbeacon.com/2015/12/29/religion-central-to-gianfortes-life-but-not-his-campaign|date=December 29, 2015|publisher=''Flathead Beacon''|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral History ==\n{{Election box begin|title=[[Montana's at-large congressional district special election, 2017]]<ref name=GenElection2017>{{cite web |url= http://mtelectionresults.gov/resultsSW.aspx?type=FED&map=CTY |title= 2017 Special Election (unofficial results) |publisher= Montana Secretary of State |accessdate= May 26, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|candidate=Greg Gianforte|party=Republican Party (United States)|votes=189,473|percentage=50.19%|change=-6.00}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=[[Rob Quist]]|votes=166,483|percentage=44.11%|change=+3.46}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Mark L Wicks|votes=21,509|percentage=5.70%|change=+2.44}}\n{{Election box majority|votes=22,990|percentage=6.10%|change=-7.54%}}\n{{Election box turnout|votes=377,465|percentage=54.22%|change=-20.22%}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|winner=Republican Party (United States)|swing=}}\n{{Election box end}}{{Election box begin|title=[[Montana gubernatorial election, 2016]]<ref name=GeneralElection>{{cite web|url=http://mtelectionresults.gov/resultsSW.aspx?type=STATE&map=CTY |title=2016 General Election | publisher=Montana Secretary of State |accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|candidate=[[Steve Bullock (Montana politician)|Steve Bullock]] (Incumbent)|party=Democratic Party (United States)|votes=255,933|percentage=50.25|change=+1.35%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Greg Gianforte|votes=236,115|percentage=46.36|change=-0.98%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Ted Dunlap|votes=17,312|percentage=3.39|change=-0.37%}}\n{{Election box plurality||votes=19,818|percentage=3.89|change=+2.33%}}\n{{Election box 